<BaseLayout title={title}>
  <h1>Sustainable Weighted Average Cost of Capital (SWACC): Derivation & Formula</h1>

  <section>
    <h2>Why a New Cost of Capital Measure?</h2>
    <p>
      Traditional WACC methods fail to reflect sustainability, resource depletion, or intergenerational equity in extractive industries.
      <strong>The SWACC formula</strong>, introduced in this research, directly embeds user-cost economics and sustainability:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Accounts for <strong>resource depletion and environmental costs</strong>.</li>
      <li>Incorporates <strong>intergenerational equity and societal expectations</strong> into the cost of capital.</li>
      <li>Corrects WACC's failure to incentivize future-proof investment.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Step-by-Step SWACC Derivation</h2>
    <h3>1. User-Cost Principle</h3>
    <p>
      The user cost represents the portion of rent reserved for future generations:
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <span class="katex">
      UC = Resource Rent × (1 - NPV<sub>Reinvestment</sub> / NPV<sub>Extraction</sub>)
      </span>
    </blockquote>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Resource Rent:</strong> Profits after costs, taxes, and royalties.</li>
      <li><strong>NPV<sub>Reinvestment</sub>:</strong> Present value of all future-proofing capital expenditures.</li>
      <li><strong>NPV<sub>Extraction</sub>:</strong> Present value of extraction cash flows.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <strong>Interpretation:</strong> Higher reinvestment reduces the user cost, meaning more sustainable practice.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Sustainable CapEx Share</h3>
    <p>
      The sustainable CapEx share rewards green and social investments:
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <span class="katex">
      Sustainable CapEx Share = CapEx<sub>Sustainable</sub> / Total CapEx
      </span>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      This ratio directly influences both user-cost deduction and SWACC.
    </p>

    <h3>3. SWACC Formula</h3>
    <blockquote>
      <span class="katex">
      SWACC = [w<sub>e</sub>·r<sub>e</sub> + w<sub>d</sub>·r<sub>d</sub>·(1-T)] + User Cost Adjustment
      </span>
    </blockquote>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>w<sub>e</sub>, w<sub>d</sub>:</strong> Weights for equity and debt.</li>
      <li><strong>r<sub>e</sub>, r<sub>d</sub>:</strong> Costs of equity and debt.</li>
      <li><strong>T:</strong> Marginal tax rate.</li>
      <li><strong>User Cost Adjustment:</strong> Penalizes low sustainable reinvestment.</li>
    </ul>
    <blockquote>
      <span class="katex">
      User Cost Adjustment = User Cost / Total Invested Capital
      </span>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      If sustainable CapEx is high, the adjustment shrinks; if low, SWACC increases, penalizing unsustainable practice.
    </p>

    <h3>4. Final SWACC Equation</h3>
<blockquote>
  <span class="katex">
    SWACC = [w<sub>e</sub>·r<sub>e</sub> + w<sub>d</sub>·r<sub>d</sub>·(1-T)] + 
    (Resource Rent × (1 - NPV<sub>Reinvestment</sub> / NPV<sub>Extraction</sub>) / Total Invested Capital)
  </span>
</blockquote>
<p>
      <strong>This formula is novel, evidence-based, and quantifiable.</strong>
      It provides a new benchmark for sustainable finance in extractive industries.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why SWACC Matters</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Penalizes “eating the seed corn”</strong> – SWACC grows for companies failing to reinvest sustainably.</li>
      <li><strong>Rewards future-proofing</strong> – Companies investing in green, circular, or social assets are favored.</li>
      <li><strong>Aligns with planetary boundaries</strong> and intergenerational justice.</li>
      <li><strong>Practical</strong> – Can be calculated for any company with adequate financial data.</li>
    </ul>
